 on a single cloud or part of a cloud bank, usually from a nearby mountaintop or while flying. It causes 1,000 cubic feet of cloud per level of the caster to become solid enough to support any weight. The solidified clouds remain airborne and fee
l like a thick carpet.
\par \tab A creature that falls onto the magically strengthened cloud sustains falling damage per the }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 PH}{\fs24\cgrid0 , p. 104. An animal or individual th
at flies into the solidified cloud falls, stunned, for a round and must make a successful Dexterity check to recover. If a creature is flying through a cloud at the moment it becomes solidified, it may make a saving throw vs. petrification. Those who succ
eed escape the cloud in time. Creatures that fail the save become trapped as the cloud solidifies around them. However, as the cloud is porous, they can continue to breathe until the spell's duration elapses.
\par \tab The solidified cloud itself continues to drift with the wind as usual. While the caster cannot use this particular spell to propel the cloud at all, a }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 control winds}{\fs24\cgrid0 
