\par }{\b\fs28\cf13\cgrid0 New Magical Items
\par }{\fs24\cgrid0 
\par \tab Druid characters can use the magical items generally permitted priests 
except written ones, such as scrolls or books. They can wear magical armor only when it is natural, such as wooden shields. Any magical weapon a druid uses must be of a type permitted to priests, as well as by the character's druidic kit and branch.

\par \tab This section contains new magical items that fit the druid's role of Nature priest, keeper of the balance, and dweller in the country. In addition, a small number of the items are designed for use against druids.
\par \tab Although this listing contains some powerful items, many are fairly low-key. Items like the }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 bountiful spade}{\fs24\cgrid0 , or}{\i\fs24\cgrid0  seeds of plenty}{\fs24\cgrid0 
 represent the kind of magical item a high-level character would create as a gift for a favored farmer or lord. Druids might offer cursed items like the }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 necklace of beast speech}{\fs24\cgrid0 
 to someone as punishment for wronging the Order or the land.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\cf13\cgrid0 Creating Magical Items
\par }{\fs24\cgrid0 \tab 
\par \tab The normal rules for priests creating magical items (}{\i\fs24\cgrid0 DMG}{\fs24\cgrid0  pgs. 83-88) apply to druids as well. In almost all cases, gathering the rare, unique, or impossible component
s and combining them properly remains more important than purchasing expensive materials; quest and ritual take precedence over the depth of the druid's purse.
\par \tab The personal touch is vital: Druids must make the vessels for enchantment using their nonweapon
 proficiencies. Characters needn't be expert artisans, but they cannot create a magical scimitar merely by enchanting a weapon someone else has made. As a result, a druid who completes an arduous series of tasks to collect the necessary components may not
 actually have to spend any money to build the item, although major magical items require components easily worth the 1,000 to 10,000 gp noted in the }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 DMG}{\fs24\cgrid0  (p. 87).
\par \tab Priest characters must spend up to three weeks meditating, fasting, and purifying themselves 
before they can enchant an item. Druids must begin this process at a sacred time, like an equinox, for the enchantment to have any chance of success. Druids purify the vessel and pray for its consecration not at an altar, but at their grove.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\cf13\cgrid0 Potions
\par }{\fs24\cgrid0 \tab 
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Potion of Plant Health.}{\fs24\cgrid0 
 This potion vitalizes a living plant when poured upon its roots. It cures the plant's illnesses and keeps it free from natural parasites and disease for a year. During this time, the plant grows 50% better than normal, and 10% better 
than normal the next year. Edible fruit, berries, or sap from the plant taste unusually succulent, while flowering plants bloom exceptionally well. If a vegetable monster such as a treant or shambling mound drinks this potion, treat it as a }{
\i\fs24\cgrid0 potion of extra-healing.}{\fs24\cgrid0  XP value: 400.
\par 
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Sap of the Eldest Tree.}{\fs24\cgrid0 
 Usually found in an earthen flask, this potion resembles thick corn or maple syrup. Characters who drink the sap (or bake it in a cake and eat it) will not age a day for the next 10 years! However, unlike a }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 longevity}{\fs24\cgrid0 
 potion, it does not make the drinker any younger. A person must consume the entire potion to gain the full benefit; if five characters share the syrup, each stops aging for two years. Additional doses are not cumulative--later imbibings supplan
t earlier ones. XP value: 500.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\cf13\cgrid0 Wands and Staves}{\fs24\cgrid0 
\par \tab 
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Wand of Shape Binding.}{\fs24\cgrid0  Characters often use this item }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 against}{\fs24\cgrid0 
 druids. When hit by its multicolored beam (projected up to 80 feet), beings with the ability to shapechange or polymorph must save vs. wands a
t a -3 penalty. Victims who fail cannot voluntarily alter shape for 2d10 turns. Attempts to shift shape using spells, magical items, or innate powers result in failure. A use of this rechargeable wand consumes one charge per 4 HD or levels of the subject.
 XP value: 800.
\par 
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Wanderer's Staff.}{\fs24\cgrid0  This resembles a stout oaken staff, which radiates magic and, in fact, functions as a }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 quarterstaff +1.}{\fs24\cgrid0 
 However, its primary power is locomotion. If carried as a walking stick, users hiking at a steady pace do not tire or need sleep. Any time spent walking counts as sleep for the purpose of resting the character. If desired, the character can walk night an
d day, taking only brief breaks for food, drink, etc. XP value: 2,000.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\cf13\cgrid0 Rings
\par }{\fs24\cgrid0 \tab 
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Ring of the Hierophant.}{\fs24\cgrid0  Only druids can utilize this ring, which enables characters to speak the language of elementals. This, the ring's lesser power, uses up no charges.
\par \tab Mor
e impressively, a druid wearing the ring may shapechange into an elemental. Druids in elemental form retain their own hit points and saving throws, but otherwise possess the characteristics of a 12 HD elemental. The transformation functions just like a dr
u
id's shapechanging power this rechargeable ring even restores hit points when the druid changes back. However, transformations last only for a maximum of one hour. Each elemental form (air, fire, earth, and water) may be assumed only once per month. XP va
lue: 4,000.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\cf13\cgrid0 Weapons
\par }{\fs24\cgrid0 \tab 
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Lunar Sickle.}{\fs24\cgrid0  This weapon, a sickle crafted from silver and bound to the moon, m
ay have been forged for druids as a symbol of the cyclic nature of time. The sickle boasts its greatest strength during the waxing moon. It has a +2 bonus from the new moon to half moon, a +3 bonus from the half moon to full moon, and +4 during the full m
oon. When the moon begins to wane, the}{\i\fs24\cgrid0  lunar sickle}{\fs24\cgrid0 
 drops to a +1 bonus. During the dark of the moon it loses all magical bonuses; until the new moon rises, it no longer affects creatures that can be hit only by magical weapons. XP value: 1,500.
\par 
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Sickle of the Harvest.}{\fs24\cgrid0  This sickle appears to be a normal farm implement, albeit of superior quality. If used in combat, it functions as a +1 weapon. However, its real power is as a magical harvesting tool.
\par \tab Anyone who grasps the sickle and speaks in the secret lan
guage of the druids can order the sickle to harvest a field on its own. When so commanded, the sickle takes to the air and harvests up to half an acre of grain per turn. It can accept precise orders, such as, "Cut down all stalks of ripe grain within a mi
le, save for Farmer Dowd's field."
\par \tab The sickle continues working until: three hours pass; its owner orders it to stop; or it moves a mile from its owner. Characters can also halt the sickle by destroying it or snatching it out of the air. Anyone trying to g
rab the sickle must make a successful attack roll against AC -4. Those who fail suffer 1d6+1 points of damage; success means a character grabs it and stops the harvesting.
\par \tab Treat attacks on the sickle as attacks against a }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 sword of dancing}{\fs24\cgrid0 ; the sickle, while physically unstoppable, can be affected by failing a saving roll against a spell such as }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 fireball, lightning bolt}{
\fs24\cgrid0 , or }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 transmute metal to wood}{\fs24\cgrid0 . 
\par XP value: 1,300.
\par 
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Heartwood Cudgel.}{\fs24\cgrid0  This club, made from the heartwood of an oak, is a }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 club +1-- club +2}{\fs24\cgrid0  in a druid's hands. XP value: 500.
\par 
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Mistletoe Dart.}{\fs24\cgrid0  The body and tip of this dart are fashioned from enchanted mistletoe. Magical armor, shields, or rings give no bonus protection against it; for example, a person wearing }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 chain mail +4}{
\fs24\cgrid0  would have AC 5, not AC 1. Darts, while not innately poisonous, can be coated with any venom. Characters usually find these darts in groups of 2 to 8 (2d4). XP value: 50 each.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\cf13\cgrid0 Armor
\par }{\fs24\cgrid0 \tab 
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Antlered Helm.}{\fs24\cgrid0  This metal-reinforced leather helm, adorned with a stag's antlers, allows the wearer to run like a deer, with a base movement rate of 18. Moreover, stags and deer see, hear, and smell wearers of an }{
\i\fs24\cgrid0 antlered helm}{\fs24\cgrid0  as if they were stags, and react accordingly. This power makes the item very useful for hunting. XP value: 800.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\cf13\cgrid0 Miscellaneous Magic
\par }{\fs24\cgrid0 \tab 
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Bountiful Spade.}{\fs24\cgrid0  Characters who use this enchanted farm implement to turn over the earth prior to planting a field receive a +3 bonus on their agriculture proficiency check for that year. XP value: 500.
\par 
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Cloak of the Beasts.}{\fs24\cgrid0  This plain brown
