\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Awakened Plants.}{\fs24\cgrid0  The grove's magic has "awakened" 1d3 10-foot-square patches of weeds, creepers, or bushes with semi-intelligence, 4 Hit Dice, AC 10, and the ability to attack as an }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 entangle}{
\fs24\cgrid0  spell. They will act to protect themselves and defend the grove.
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Bountiful.}{\fs24\cgrid0  If t
he sacred grove contains plants that produce edible fruit, nuts, or berries, 3d6+20 enchanted examples sprout each spring along with the usual crop. The magic fruit, nuts, or berries--the largest and most healthy of their species--confer the benefits of a
 }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 goodberry}{\fs24\cgrid0  spell's products on the characters who eat them. Once picked, no more will grow until the following year.
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Control Temperature.}{\fs24\cgrid0  Any Nature worshiper in the grove may make a grove's temperature rise or fall within 30 degrees. This ability, possibl
e once per day, affects the entire grove. Arctic or desert groves commonly feature this power, which enables those in the grove to survive brief climatic extremes, especially combined with the power to still winds (below).
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Faerie Fire.}{\fs24\cgrid0  A Nature worshiper (even a nonpriest) may cause a }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 faerie fire}{\fs24\cgrid0 
 luminance to appear, centered on the character or upon any of the trees, rocks, or standing stones in the grove. The }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 faerie fire}{\fs24\cgrid0 , which lasts one turn per level of the caller, can be summoned once per person in a 
given day. }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 Faerie fire}{\fs24\cgrid0  that druids call endures for two turns per level of the druid and can flicker about the grove at will. When a druid casts a}{\i\fs24\cgrid0  faerie fire}{\fs24\cgrid0 
 spell within the grove, its duration triples.
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Healing.}{\fs24\cgrid0  Beings of neutral alignment or those alli
ed to the druid may heal wounds at twice the rate of natural healing while in the magical sacred grove. Healing-related spells produce the maximum benefits; for instance, }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 cure light wounds}{\fs24\cgrid0  restores 8 points of damage.

\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Prophecy.}{\fs24\cgrid0  A druid who spends the nigh
t sleeping in the grove may receive a magical portent in a dream concerning the past, present, or future. The nature of the prophecy remains the DM's decision, but it should never contain more information than would come to light using a properly cast }{
\i\fs24\cgrid0 commune with nature}{\fs24\cgrid0  spell. The portent usually warns of danger or hints at a task Nature wishes the druid to perform.
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Protective Aura.}{\fs24\cgrid0  Any creature but a druid, dryad, or nymph who sees the grove must save vs. spell. Those who fail perceive the grove as nothi
ng other than a normal clearing (or the like) until they are led into it. The sacred grove also generates a continual protective field similar to }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 protection from evil, 10' radius,}{\fs24\cgrid0 
 except it covers the entire grove and has the powers of both }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 protection from evil}{\fs24\cgrid0  and }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 protection from good}{\fs24\cgrid0  spells.
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Still Winds.}{\fs24\cgrid0  Worshipers of Nature in the sacred grove (even nonpriests) can cause winds to calm for up to one turn per level, as long as they concentrate on maintaining this power. Triple the duration when a druid in
vokes it. This power, possible once per day, is quite common in desert, mountain, and arctic groves, as it protects the sacred grove and those in it from sandstorms, tornadoes, or snowstorms, and the like.
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Sweet Water.}{\fs24\cgrid0  Water from a source within the grove or dew gathered from the grass in the area has the properties of }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 sweet water}{\fs24\cgrid0 
, but loses these special properties as soon as it is removed from the site.
\par \tab }{\b\fs24\cgrid0 Special.}{\fs24\cgrid0  The DM can create a power associated with the branch or kit of the druid that sanctified thi
s grove. For instance, the grove of a Hivemaster might contain a wasp's nest or beehive from which a druid could call an }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 insect plague}{\fs24\cgrid0 
 once per day, while a swamp druid's grove could feature a patch of firm ground that turns suddenly to quicksandlike mud (as in a }{\i\fs24\cgrid0 rock to mud}{\fs24\cgrid0  spell).
